    <h2>communities of practice</h2>
    <div class="flourish-embed" data-src="story/4029"></div><script src="https://public.flourish.studio/resources/embed.js"></script>
  </div>
  <div class="fl w-40 tj pa4">
    
      
        <p class="f6 bg-dark-red light-gray"><a href="/tags/need"> <i class="fa fa-heart" style="color:white"></i></a> "Like all Americans, we seem too anxious to buy gadgets and conveniences that we should do without. All too many of the oppressed of the earth use such conveniences as opiates. A group of people that are always the last hired, the first fired, and are always relegated to the least desirable jobs, should be careful how they spend their money when they get it."<br />‚ÄìLaureen White, <em>Arkansas State Press,</em> May 15, 1953</p>
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
        <p class="f6 bg-yellow"><a href="/tags/tool"> <i class="fa fa-wrench" style="color:gray"></i></a> "‚Ä¶electric fans, refrigerators and washing machines, vacuum cleaners and gramophones.  The new gadgets may be highly valued in themselves for the increased comfort or convenience which they bring, or for their effect in reducing household drudgery and saving time."<br />‚ÄìRonald Philip Dore,	<em>City Life in Japan</em> (1958)</p>
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
        <p class="f6 bg-green light-gray"><a href="/tags/gauge"> <i class="fa fa-tachometer-alt" style="color:white"></i></a> "Women request mechanical gadgets that they can operate with a minimum of effort. And today's car has been so tailored to the woman's tastes that the automobile has taken on a whole new group of functions that men alone would not have dared to demand for themselves with such conveniences as power steering, power brakes, seating adjustments and electric window lifts."<br />‚Äì<em>The Plain Dealer,</em> Sept 10, 1954</p>
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
        <p class="f6 bg-purple light-gray"><a href="/tags/wrinkle"> <i class="fa fa-bolt" style="color:white"></i></a> "Because she hated to hear her favorite surgeon grumble, Registered Nurse Meloneze Robinson became an inventor. ‚ÄúWhy,‚Äù asked Dr. Asa Yancey, each time he was to perform an amputation, ‚Äúdoesn‚Äôt someone devise a simple method to keep the patient‚Äôs limb immobile during the operation?‚Äù At her post at the Tuskegee Veterans Administration hospital, Nurse Robinson devised the first amputation surgery limb support, shown above. Dr. Yancey was the first to use the gadget after it was patented after two years work, $800 and tons of anxiety."<br />‚Äì<em>Los Angeles Tribune,</em> Jan 15, 1960</p>
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
        <p class="f6 bg-dark-blue light-gray"><a href="/tags/rig"> <i class="fa fa-lightbulb" style="color:white"></i></a> "We made a wooden platform for the tents to keep their floors dry and hold the tents straight -- the stakes had not held in the wet ground. Down at the river we made a trap that funneled fish into a wire cage, and from a simple roof and frame and some of the mosquito netting we built a mosquito-proof gazebo where we could congregate. These were gadgets, not inventions, but they made life more comfortable, and within very few days I could see the skeleton of a settlement in Jeronimo."<br />‚ÄìPaul Theroux, <em>Mosquito Coast</em> (1981)</p>
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
      
    
